Honor code

For this problem set I worked with:

Setup

Load necessary packages:

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(babynames)

Question 1

In this exercise, youre going to recreate the figure from Midterm I, Question 4, allowing us to visualize the degree to which the names Casey and Riley were used for babies of both sex male and female.

Part a)

Perform the data wrangling necessary to transform the babynames data frame included in the babynames package into a new data frame called babynames_riley_casey that will allow us to create the visualization.

Hint: I recommend you first draw on a piece of paper what the data frame should look like; that way youll know what your target looks like and when youve hit it.

babynames_riley_casey <- babynames %>%
  filter(name == "Riley" | name == "Casey")

Part b)

Recreate the above visualization exactly, right down to the manually set colors of the lines ("forestgreen" and "orange") and the capitalization of all text.

ggplot(babynames_riley_casey, aes(x=year, y=prop, col=sex)) +
  geom_line() +
  facet_wrap(~name) +
  labs(x = "Year", y = "Proportion", color = "Sex", title = "Comparison of Casey and Riley") +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("forestgreen", "orange"))

Part c)

Once again, recreate the above figure exactly, however this time add an appropriately chosen trend lines. For claritys sake, do NOT include the standard error bars.

ggplot(babynames_riley_casey, aes(x=year, y=prop, col=sex)) +
  geom_line(size = 1) +
  facet_wrap(~name) +
  labs(x = "Year", y = "Proportion", color = "Sex", title = "Comparison of Casey and Riley") +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("forestgreen", "orange")) +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE, size = 0.5, linetype = "dashed")

Bonus

In this exercise, youre going to once again recreate the figure from Midterm I, Question 4. This time however, youre going to limit it to years 1960 and later:

Part a)

Perform the data wrangling necessary to transform the babynames data frame included in the babynames package into a new data frame babynames_riley_casey_1960_later that only has data for 1960 or later.

Hint There are many ways to do this. The following hint may (or may not) prove useful depending which way you choose: Precedence of Logical Operators.

# This will be incorrect, because it will filter all rows that:
# -Have name "Casey" and year >= 1960
# OR those rows that
# -Have name "Riley"
babynames_riley_casey_1960_later <- babynames %>%
  filter(name == "Riley" | name == "Casey" & year >= 1960) 

# Whereas this will be correct:
babynames_riley_casey_1960_later <- babynames %>%
  filter((name == "Riley" | name == "Casey") & year >= 1960) 

# As well as using filter() twice
babynames_riley_casey_1960_later <- babynames %>%
  filter(name == "Riley" | name == "Casey") %>% 
  filter(year >= 1960)

Part b)

Recreate the above visualization exactly, right down to the colors of the lines which were manually set to be "forestgreen" and "orange" and the capitalization of all text. However this time, the x-axis should only be for years 1960 and later, as saved in the babynames_riley_casey_1960_later data frame.

ggplot(babynames_riley_casey_1960_later, aes(x=year, y=prop, col=sex)) +
  geom_line() +
  facet_wrap(~name) +
  labs(x = "Year", y = "Proportion", color = "Sex", title = "Comparison of Casey and Riley") +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("forestgreen", "orange"))
